avery demonstrates that the family ties that bind the genre’s normative heterosexuality are far more tenuous than we have been led to believe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHeterosexuality. 0aHomosexuality on television. 0aSex role on television. 0aSituation comedies (Television programs)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSituation comedies (Television programs)zUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059134?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059134/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles